HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 39
By Love
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Donald Majors, Jr., of
Nashville.
WHEREAS, we were greatly saddened to learn of the passing of Donald Majors, Jr., of
Nashville; and
WHEREAS, Don Majors was an exemplary public servant and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, the son of Donald Majors, Sr., and Helen Majors, Don Majors was born and
raised in Nashville, where he resided his entire life; and
WHEREAS, after marrying his devoted wife, Vallie Majors, he moved to Parkwood,
where he became a superb baseball coach for the Parkwood Dixie Youth Baseball program,
eventually serving as the director of the program for twelve years; and
WHEREAS, his time with the Parkwood Dixie Youth Baseball program, which included
rescuing the Parkwood ballfield altogether, broke the color barrier in the Dixie League and within
the Sertoma Club; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Majors joined the Metropolitan Council as a representative for the
Maplewood region and helped to break the color barrier for minority contracting, taking on
powerful players in Nashville to establish equity; and
WHEREAS, skilled in diplomacy and abundant in charisma, Mr. Majors deftly utilized his
verbal prowess to work for the common good in Nashville politics; and
WHEREAS, he also spent twelve years as a congressional aide, advisor, constituent
services specialist, and field representative for former U.S. Representative Jim Cooper, who
