fondly remembers Mr. Majors and his team working tirelessly in the Nashville Downtown Public
Library to remedy the various ills of local citizens; and
WHEREAS, when he was not giving of himself for the concerns of his constituency, Mr.
Majors enjoyed playing, congregating around, or even simply thinking about golf, which he
played with the Nashville Duffers; and
WHEREAS, he was also deeply devoted to his family and always endeavored to remain
true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, Donald Majors, Jr., will be sadly mourned yet fondly remembered by his
wife, Vallie Majors; his children, Sharon Barksdale and Brandon Majors; his grandchildren,
Franshaska Barksdale, Aubrei Barksdale, and Vallie Lashae Majors; his siblings, Debra (Steve)
Bell, Janice Majors, and Jerry Majors; and many other relatives and friends; and
WHEREAS, in addition to his father and mother, he was preceded in death by his
brother, Thomas Oakley Majors; and
WHEREAS, Don Majors leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should remember the bountiful life of this exceptional
gentleman and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Donald Majors, Jr., reflecting fondly upon his
impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage and
conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Majors.
